Research Question

Our main research question is to explore the differences in heart disease mortality in Scotland, and to identify how mortality rates vary across different demographic categories, such as gender, geographical area, age group, and year. The goal is to identify any long-term patterns or to determine whether certain groups consistently exhibit higher mortality rates than others. We also aim to provide risk predictions for the population of Scotland through the use of modelling.

This particular dataset interested our group as heart diseases can affect anyone and is also known as one of the main causes of death globally. We all have a risk of getting heart disease and it was interesting to us to find what group of people are most at risk.

Data Overview

We are using the Heart Disease Mortality by Council Area dataset from the Scottish Heart Disease Statistics from the Public Health Scotland NHS website, which we named MArea.

This dataset consists of 17820 rows and 14 variables (columns).

Our focus was on the different demographic and geographic categories, so from the start we cleaned up the data from MArea into Data where there are 7230 rows and 7 variables (columns):

Variable Description Type
Year Year of recorded data Numeric
CA Council area code Categorical
AgeGroup Defined age range Categorical
Sex Male or female Categorical
Diagnosis Specific heart-disease-related diagnosis Categorical
CrudeRate Raw mortality rate Numeric
EASR European Age-Standardised Rate Numeric

Additionally to support our research aim, we made additional variables to categorise our data better and so we could analyse and evaluate the data more easily. The additional variables will be mentioned in the findings.

Data Visualisations

To understand more about this dataset, we tried to find more patterns by making visualisations

1. EASR

Firstly, we compared the EASR and crude rate in this dataset. The EASR is the European Age-Sex standardised rate per 100,000 population. It is adjusted for the age distribution using a standard population (100,000) and provides a more valid and unbiased comparison than crude rate.

We used the EASR and plotted it against crude rate to see how reliable and it was and we plotted a line of best fit, which had a gradient of 1. This shows that crude rate is very reliable and we can confidently use it to compare evaluate the data, as their correlation is near perfect. Therefore we used the crude rate instead of EASR for the rest of the investigation.

2. Geographical area

To start off, we tried to find if there were differences in mortality rate for each region of Scotland. We looked at the dataset CouncilArea from CouncilArea.csv and we manually matched each area with the council area codes in MArea (the original dataset) to each region (North, Central, South, etc.)

We found that there was not much variation across the regions except for the North-east, where rates are relatively around 5% higher than the other regions. We concluded that there is no trend between geographical location and crude rate for heart diseases, and we decided that this is not something we had to keep looking into. This could also mean that the risk factors such as oil intake or physical activity are quite similar throughout each region. So we decided to investigate the other factors in this dataset.

3. Sex

Then, to visualise the how the crude rate differs between sex, we made a bar chart with the mean value of crude rates across all men and women.

We found that men have a significantly higher mean crude rate than women, almost double. This shows that men are more twice as likely to die from heart diseases than women This may be caused by eating habits, physical activity, or even biological reasons. We figured this was worth looking into.

Significant gender differences: The average CrudeRate of men (47.9) is 72% higher than that of women (27.8), but the median for both is 0, indicating that most individuals have no events, but men have more extreme high-risk cases. The global median (1.95) falls between men and women, indicating that the dataset may contain mixed gender ratios.

4. Age

We then investigated the different age groups differed in crude rate.

The clear takeaway form this visualisation is 75 plus year olds have the highest mean crude rate. This tells us that this group of people (aged 75 plus) are most likely to suffer from heart disease.

Howeverm the mean and median of all ages are close (72.8 vs 72.3) and relatively lower, but after splitting, it can be seen that using global statistics will ignore high-risk elderly groups.

5. Year

We then compared mean crude rate with year, visualising it with a line chart.

We found that the mean crude rate falls throughout the years until 2019, where it increases at a faster rate. This does not tell us much about if the year has any correlation with crude rate, but it shows how it has changed over the years and we could use it to compare with other variables.

6. Diagnosis

Finally, for the single variables, we looked at the diagnoses and how crude rate differed between the three.

This visualisation does not tell us much, but we can clearly see the distribution of deaths among the three diagnoses, with coronary heart diseases with the highest rate, followed by heart attacks, and heart failure with the lowest rate.

Coronary heart disease: The mean and median values are close (116.0 vs 112.0), indicating a relatively symmetrical data distribution, stable risk, and generally high risk. Heart failure: The mean (2.32) is much higher than the median (0), indicating that the vast majority of cases have no events, but there are a small number of individuals with extremely high risk.

7. Combining variables

After investigating each variable individually against the mean crude rate, we figured that each variable did not tell us much on its own. This led us into combining variables together, comparing two variables together with crude rate.

Predictive Modelling

Data Processing

After removing all observations labeled as ALL in the Sex and AgeGroup variables, the dataset contains 3068 valid records.

We excluded these categories because they represent aggregated totals and could distort the accuracy of the model by mixing population groups with very different characteristics.

Data<-Data%>% 
  filter(!Sex %in% c("All"))%>%
  filter(!AgeGroup %in% c("All"))

Grouping

Data <- Data %>%
  mutate(
    split_AgeGroup = case_when(
      AgeGroup %in% c("75plus years") ~ "75plus years",
      AgeGroup %in% c("0-44 years", "45-64 years", "65-74 years", "under75 years") ~ "under75 years",
      TRUE ~ "Others"
      )
  )


Data$split_AgeGroup<-relevel(factor(Data$split_AgeGroup),ref="under75 years")
Data$Diagnosis<-relevel(factor(Data$Diagnosis),ref="Heart Failure")
Data$Sex<-relevel(factor(Data$Sex),ref="Females")

Coefficient Interpretation

ht_yc_fit_1 <- linear_reg() %>%
  set_engine("lm") %>%
  fit(CrudeRate ~ Year+split_AgeGroup+Sex+Diagnosis ,data = Data)
tidy(ht_yc_fit_1)

Year:

The coefficient for Year is extremely small, indicating that time has minimal or no linear effect on crude mortality rate. This aligns with the visual scatter plot showing stable mortality levels across the years.

AgeGroup:

The 75+ age group has the largest estimated coefficient, making it the strongest predictor of crude mortality rate. This reflects the well-known increased cardiovascular risk among older populations.

Sex:

The coefficient for males is positive and significant, showing that male groups have higher mortality rates than females. This confirms that gender is an important demographic factor.

Diagnosis:

Both Coronary Heart Disease and Heart Attack categories have noticeably large coefficient estimates. These diagnosis types are therefore also major contributors to increased mortality rate.

Importance Ranking (from least to most influential):

Year < Is Male < Is Heart Attack < Is Coronary Heart Disease < Is Age 75+

Residual Plot Analysis

ht_yc_fit_aug_1 <- augment(ht_yc_fit_1$fit)
ggplot(ht_yc_fit_aug_1, mapping = aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color = "gray", lty = "dashed") +
  labs(x = "Predicted CrudeRate", y = "Residuals")

The residual plot shows several important patterns:

1. Clustered residuals with a large empty gap

Residuals concentrate on the left and right sides of the predicted scale, with very few observations between predicted values 100200. This structure may caused by: Most groups have low crude mortality ratesOnly specific groups (e.g., 75+ or certain diagnoses) have very high mortality.Hence,this creates natural gaps in the distribution, independent of the model

2. Fan-shaped pattern

The residuals spread out more widely as the predicted value increases, forming a fan shape.

Possible reasons include: - Missing important predictors (e.g., regional differences, socioeconomic factors) - Non-linear relationships that the linear model cannot capture - The limitations of simple transformations - Even after trying log(CrudeRate + 1), the distribution did not improve

This suggests that the linearity assumption may not fully hold.

ht_yc_fit_2 <- linear_reg() %>%

Conclusion

Although the linear regression model has limitations, it successfully identifies three key factors that may influence heart disease mortality:

  1. Age group (especially 75+)
  2. Sex (male)
  3. Diagnosis type (Coronary Heart Disease, Heart Attack)

Suggestions for Improvement

  1. Include additional variables or perform subgroup analysis to improve the models explanatory power (e.g., add regional effects, socioeconomic indicators)

  2. Use a larger dataset such as all regions of the UK to test whether the observed patterns remain consistent

  3. Consider exploring non-linear models or classification models (e.g., logistic regression) for further insights

logistic regression model

We have developed a binary classification model (high-risk and low-risk) aimed at risk prediction in a Scottish population.

Method: The median population mortality rate was used as the cutoffindividuals above the median were labeled high-risk, and those below were labeled low-risk. Eighty percent of the data were used for training and 20 % for testing.

CA <- Data %>% 
  mutate(rate = CrudeRate / 1000) %>% 
  mutate(rate_group = if_else(rate <= median(rate, na.rm = TRUE), 0, 1)) %>% 
  mutate(rate_group = factor(rate_group))

set.seed(888)
CrudeRate_split <- initial_split(CA, prop = 0.80)

train_data <- training(CrudeRate_split)
test_data  <- testing(CrudeRate_split)

CrudeRate_fit <- logistic_reg() %>%
  set_engine("glm") %>%
  fit(rate_group ~ AgeGroup + Sex + Diagnosis,
      data = train_data,
      fimily = "binomial")

CrudeRate_pred <- predict(CrudeRate_fit, test_data, type = "prob") %>%
  bind_cols(test_data)

AUC_ROC <- CrudeRate_pred %>%
  roc_curve(
    truth = rate_group,
    .pred_1,
    event_level = "second"
  )
  
AUC_ROC %>% autoplot()

From the ROC curve we can draw the following conclusions: The point near the bottom-left corner shows both sensitivity and (1 specificity) close to 0, indicating that very few low-mortality individuals are misclassified as high-risk. However, this also means that only a small proportion of true high-mortality individuals are correctly identified; in other words, the model frequently misclassifies high-mortality people as low-risk. The steep early rise from the bottom-left corner demonstrates strong discriminatory power: even small differences in predictor values allow the model to capture many additional high-risk cases without simultaneously flagging large numbers of low-risk subjects. Overall, the curve bows toward the upper-left corner, suggesting that the model performs well.

best_cutoff <- AUC_ROC %>%
  mutate(J = sensitivity + specificity - 1) %>%
  filter(J == max(J)) %>%
  select(.threshold, sensitivity, specificity, J)

best_cutoff
## # A tibble: 1  4
##   .threshold sensitivity specificity     J
##        <dbl>       <dbl>       <dbl> <dbl>
## 1     0.0850        0.72       0.855 0.575

We calculated the Youden Index as sensitivity + specificity 1 and selected the cutoff that maximizes this index. At this optimal cutoff the model achieves: Sensitivity = 0.72 Specificity = 0.8551237 These are the best attainable values given the data.

cutoff_prob <- best_cutoff$.threshold
CrudeRate_pred %>%
  mutate(
    rate_group      = if_else(rate_group == 1 , "high_CrudeRate", "low_CrudeRate"),
    rate_group_pred = if_else(.pred_1 > cutoff_prob, "labelled high-CrudeRate", "labelled low-CrudeRate")
  ) %>%
  count(rate_group_pred, rate_group) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = rate_group, values_from = n) %>%
  kable(col.names = c(" ","high_CrudeRate","low_CrudeRate"))
high_CrudeRate low_CrudeRate
labelled high-CrudeRate 33 53
labelled low-CrudeRate 17 513

Among the high-mortality group, 33 were correctly predicted and 17 were misclassified; in the low-mortality group, 513 were correctly predicted and 53 were misclassified. This demonstrates that the model is more accurate for low-mortality individuals, with only a 10 % chance of error.

CrudeRate_pred %>%
  roc_auc(
    truth = rate_group,
    .pred_1,
    event_level = "second"
  )
## # A tibble: 1  3
##   .metric .estimator .estimate
##   <chr>   <chr>          <dbl>
## 1 roc_auc binary         0.842

The area under the ROC curve (AUC) is 0.842. A higher AUC indicates better performance, so this value confirms that the model is of good quality.

Overall, age, gender, and disease are sufficient to screen out high-risk individuals, making it a very good model.
